"""
mkt-christ | judges | ch4–6 fill
present: ch4:v1,4,9,14,15,21,23; ch5:v2,4,11,20,31; ch6:v11-16,22,24,34,36,40 — 72 missing
run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-judges-4-6-fill.py

Key types:
- Deborah/Barak dual leadership: prophet + military arm (type of Christ's prophetic-warrior office)
- Jael's victory over Sisera: unexpected deliverer through weakness (1 Cor 1:25-27)
- Song of Deborah (ch5): victory hymn anticipating Rev 15:3 (song of Moses and the Lamb)
- Gideon's call (ch6): weakness-to-strength pattern; ch6 Christophany vv already present
- Fleece sign: sign from heaven; not superior to the Word but part of divine patience
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{layer}' / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{layer}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JUDGES = {
  "4": {
    "2": "<p>YHWH 'sells' Israel into the hand of Jabin — the covenant punishment language frames oppression as a divine transaction. The NT uses the same logic in reverse: Christ was 'delivered up according to the definite plan and foreknowledge of God' (Acts 2:23), sold for thirty pieces of silver (Matt 26:15), yet his being handed over was the means of purchase — he who was sold became the one who redeems all who had been sold to sin (Rom 7:14: 'sold under sin'). The pattern in every judge cycle: YHWH allows captivity so that he may accomplish redemption.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'The people of Israel cried out to YHWH for help, for he had 900 chariots of iron and he oppressed the people of Israel cruelly for twenty years.' The iron chariots of Sisera represent overwhelming military superiority — the kind of power that makes human resistance hopeless and drives the people to prayer. Christ's redemptive pattern follows the same logic: the situation must be humanly impossible for the divine solution to be recognized as such. The 'cry' (<em>zaʿaq</em>) is the covenantal distress-call that always precedes divine rescue, just as the disciples' cry in the storm (Matt 8:25) precedes the stilling of the waves.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Deborah sat under a palm tree 'between Ramah and Bethel in the hill country of Ephraim' and the people came to her for judgment. The palm is associated with royal splendor in the OT (Song 7:7-8; Ps 92:12: 'the righteous shall flourish like a palm tree'). More directly, the place of judgment under a tree anticipates Christ as the one to whom all judgment has been given (John 5:22: 'The Father judges no one but has given all judgment to the Son'). Israel came to Deborah; the nations will come to Christ (Isa 2:2-4; Rev 21:24).</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Has not YHWH, the God of Israel, commanded you, Go, gather your men at Mount Tabor?' Deborah's commission of Barak is prophetic authorization for military action — she speaks as YHWH's mouth, he acts as YHWH's arm. This two-part pattern of word and deed prefigures the relationship between the prophetic word (Scripture) and the risen Christ's power: the Word announces; the Spirit empowers; the battle is fought by the one the Word has commissioned. Tabor's later transfiguration (Matt 17:1-8) — where the divine voice again authorizes a commission — gives the mountain a second resonance in salvation history.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'I will draw out Sisera, the general of Jabin's army, to meet you by the Kishon River, with his chariots and his troops, and I will give him into your hand.' The divine 'drawing out' — YHWH himself maneuvering the enemy into position for defeat — is the theology of providential warfare. John 6:44 applies the same verb to salvation: 'No one can come to me unless the Father who sent me draws him.' The enemy is drawn into a situation where he must face the one he cannot defeat: Sisera drawn to the Kishon; sin drawn to the cross where it is defeated by the one it sought to destroy (Col 2:15).</p>",
    "8": "<p>'If you will go with me, I will go, but if you will not go with me, I will not go.' Barak's condition — his refusal to advance without Deborah's presence — is an implicit theology of divine accompaniment. The entire Judges narrative hinges on the presence or absence of YHWH with his people (2:18: 'YHWH was with the judge'). Barak's instinct — I cannot go without the divine word present — is the right instinct, if imperfectly executed. Christ's promise to his disciples mirrors and exceeds it: 'And behold, I am with you always, to the end of the age' (Matt 28:20) — the guarantee Barak sought, given unconditionally.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Barak went up with 10,000 men at his heels and Deborah with him. The 10,000 following a leader is a motif that recurs as a type of Christ's assembled army: 'The chariots of God are twice ten thousand, thousands upon thousands; the Lord is among them' (Ps 68:17). The voluntary army that follows Barak — specifically praised in the Song of Deborah (5:2, 9) as those who offered themselves willingly — prefigures the voluntary self-offering that characterizes Christ's followers: 'Your people will offer themselves freely on the day of your power, in holy garments' (Ps 110:3).</p>",
    "11": "<p>The notice about Heber the Kenite, who had separated from the main Kenite group and pitched his tent near Kedesh, is the narrative setup for Jael's act. Its Christological significance is in positioning: YHWH's providential arrangement of seemingly accidental circumstances — a tent at exactly the right location — to accomplish the unexpected deliverance. The NT names this divine preparation of circumstances: 'For we are his workmanship, created in Christ Jesus for good works, which God prepared beforehand, that we should walk in them' (Eph 2:10). Jael's tent was prepared beforehand for Sisera's end.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Sisera is told that Barak son of Abinoam has gone up to Mount Tabor — the intelligence that triggers Sisera to mobilize his iron chariot force. The enemy moves toward apparent victory; he cannot see what the prophet has already declared: 'I will give him into your hand' (v7). This is the blindness of the powers that crucified Christ: 'None of the rulers of this age understood this, for if they had, they would not have crucified the Lord of glory' (1 Cor 2:8). Sisera advances with overwhelming force to meet his defeat — the logic of every principality that moves against Christ.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Nine hundred iron chariots — the pride of Canaanite military technology — gathered at the Kishon. The iron chariot was the ancient equivalent of armored tank warfare: it represented concentrated state power applied against a relatively lightly armed infantry. That YHWH defeats such force through a woman with a tent peg is the entire message: 'for the foolishness of God is wiser than men, and the weakness of God is stronger than men' (1 Cor 1:25). The cross, viewed from outside, looked like the Roman imperial machine crushing an obscure preacher — and accomplished the defeat of every power.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'Barak pursued the chariots and the army to Harosheth-hagoyim, and all the army of Sisera fell by the edge of the sword; not a man was left.' The complete annihilation of Sisera's force — after YHWH's routing by the Kishon flood — is the type of final eschatological victory: 'the last enemy to be destroyed is death' (1 Cor 15:26). The pursuit 'not one was left' language echoes the final judgment: 'Blessed and holy is the one who shares in the first resurrection! Over such the second death has no power' (Rev 20:6). The Kishon victory is partial and temporal; Calvary and the final resurrection are its complete fulfillment.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Sisera flees on foot to the tent of Jael — his iron chariot advantage gone, he is reduced to a fugitive. The flight of the oppressor anticipates the flight of the Accuser: 'the devil who had deceived them was thrown into the lake of fire and sulfur' (Rev 20:10). Between the Kishon defeat and Jael's tent, Sisera represents the already-defeated enemy who does not yet know he has lost — the same period between Christ's resurrection (decisive defeat of sin and death) and the final judgment (complete elimination of evil's presence).</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Come in, my lord; come in to me; do not be afraid.' Jael's welcome of Sisera with false assurance — 'do not be afraid' — is a dark reversal of the divine peace-formula. Every time YHWH or his angel says 'Do not be afraid' in Scripture, it accompanies genuine deliverance and covenant peace (Isa 41:10; Luke 1:30; Rev 1:17). Jael's words parody that formula — she offers false peace to the one who will find death, not safety. The contrast underlines that true peace is only found in Christ: 'Peace I leave with you; my peace I give to you. Not as the world gives do I give to you' (John 14:27).</p>",
    "19": "<p>Jael gives Sisera milk when he asked for water, then covers him — acts of hospitality that disarm rather than deliver. The milk echoes the land's promise ('milk and honey') but here becomes the instrument of lulling the enemy to sleep before judgment. Paul's milk/solid food distinction (1 Cor 3:2; Heb 5:13) is a separate image, but the narrative logic is similar: what appears to be nourishment and rest becomes the precondition for judgment. Sisera sought water (life), received milk (abundance), and found death — a bitter reversal of covenant blessings.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Sisera commands Jael to stand at the tent door and deny his presence if anyone asks. He seeks to use her as a cover, a shield between himself and his enemies. The NT identifies a similar pattern in those who seek to use the language of Christ as cover for self-interest: 'They profess to know God, but they deny him by their works' (Titus 1:16). More directly, Sisera's attempt to hide from Barak through Jael prefigures all attempts to hide from judgment behind intermediaries — none will succeed: 'no creature is hidden from his sight, but all are naked and exposed to the eyes of him to whom we must give account' (Heb 4:13).</p>",
    "22": "<p>'And behold, as Barak was pursuing Sisera, Jael went out to meet him and said to him, Come, and I will show you the man you are seeking. So he went into her tent, and there lay Sisera dead, with the tent peg in his temple.' Deborah's prophecy (v9) is fulfilled exactly — the glory of the victory goes to a woman, not Barak. The fulfillment of prophetic word in unexpected ways is the grammar of all OT prophecy about Christ: 'Think not that I have come to abolish the Law or the Prophets; I have not come to abolish them but to fulfill them' (Matt 5:17). The word spoken by Deborah — a woman prophet — was not diminished by its unexpected fulfillment; it was vindicated.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'And the hand of the people of Israel pressed harder and harder against Jabin the king of Canaan, until they destroyed Jabin king of Canaan.' The progressive intensification of Israel's hand against Jabin — building on the Sisera victory until complete destruction — models the eschatological pattern of Christ's reign: 'For he must reign until he has put all his enemies under his feet' (1 Cor 15:25). Christ's resurrection began a reign that presses harder and harder against all remaining enemies — 'the last enemy to be destroyed is death' — until all opposition is eliminated at the final judgment.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>Then Deborah and Barak sang on that day — the victory song follows the battle as the liturgical response to salvation. The pattern is established at the Exodus: the crossing of the Red Sea is followed immediately by the Song of Moses (Exod 15:1-21). Both Revelation 15:3 ('they sang the song of Moses, the servant of God, and the song of the Lamb') and the heavenly songs of Revelation 4-5 place victory songs at the center of eschatological worship. Every song in this tradition — Deborah's, Moses', the Psalms — is a type of the final song that creation will sing when the Lamb's victory is complete.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Hear, O kings; give ear, O princes; to YHWH I will sing; I will make melody to YHWH, the God of Israel.' The call to kings and princes to attend YHWH's victory song anticipates the universal acknowledgment of Christ's lordship: 'that at the name of Jesus every knee should bow, in heaven and on earth and under the earth, and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord' (Phil 2:10-11). The song does not merely announce what happened to Sisera; it summons the power-structures of the world to recognize who won.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'The mountains quaked before YHWH, even Sinai before YHWH, the God of Israel.' The theophanic trembling of creation before YHWH connects the Kishon victory to the Sinai covenant: the same God who descended on Sinai in fire and earthquake (Exod 19:18) has descended again to rescue his people. Hebrews 12:18-29 contrasts Sinai's terrifying approach with Zion's open access through Christ's blood, but confirms that both express the same holy God: 'our God is a consuming fire' (Heb 12:29). The mountains quaking in ch5 prefigure the earthquake at Christ's death (Matt 27:51) and at the final judgment (Rev 6:14; 16:20).</p>",
    "6": "<p>In the days of Shamgar and Jael, the main roads were abandoned — travelers went by roundabout paths because of danger. The desolate highway is the condition of the world before the deliverer comes. Isaiah's prophecy of the new Exodus uses the same imagery in reverse: 'In the wilderness prepare the way of YHWH; make straight in the desert a highway for our God' (Isa 40:3), quoted by John the Baptist (Matt 3:3) as the preparation for Christ. The deserted roads of Deborah's day become the highways Christ fills; 'I am the way' (John 14:6) — the path the world had abandoned is reopened through him.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'The villagers ceased in Israel; they ceased until you arose, Deborah, arose as a mother in Israel.' The 'mother in Israel' title given to Deborah is one of the OT's most striking leadership metaphors — she embodies both the authority of a judge and the nurturing advocacy of a mother. Isaiah applies maternal imagery to YHWH himself: 'As one whom his mother comforts, so I will comfort you' (Isa 66:13). Christ's lament over Jerusalem — 'How often would I have gathered your children together as a hen gathers her brood under her wings' (Matt 23:37) — employs the same mother-bird image. Deborah's 'mother in Israel' office is a type of Christ's tender shepherding over the people of God.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'They chose new gods; then war was in the gates.' The direct causal connection between idolatry and military defeat is the Deuteronomic thesis in its most compact form: new gods → no military protection → no weapons in the hands of 40,000 Israelites. Paul makes the same diagnosis: 'For although they knew God, they did not honor him as God... therefore God gave them up' (Rom 1:21-24). The abandonment of the true God creates a vacuum that enemies fill — whether foreign armies or the spiritual forces of evil. The solution is always the same: return to YHWH, who alone gives victory.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'My heart goes out to the commanders of Israel who offered themselves willingly among the people.' The voluntary consecration praised here is the covenant ideal — fighting not under compulsion but in joyful response to YHWH's call. Psalm 110:3 (the great messianic psalm) promises that the Messiah's people will offer themselves 'freely' on his day of power: 'Your people will offer themselves freely... in holy garments.' Christ does not compel but calls; those who follow do so as free people who have grasped the worth of the one they serve (Matt 4:20: 'Immediately they left their nets and followed him').</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Awake, awake, Deborah! Awake, awake, break out in a song! Arise, Barak, lead away your captives, O son of Abinoam.' The double 'awake, awake' (<em>ûrî ûrî</em>) is the same summons Isaiah directs to Zion (Isa 51:9, 17; 52:1) and that Paul applies to the Christian life: 'Awake, O sleeper, and arise from the dead, and Christ will shine on you' (Eph 5:14). The resurrection-language of 'awake and arise' runs from the Song of Deborah through Isaiah to the NT as the summons of divine power calling the sleeping and dead to life and action.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Then down marched the remnant of the noble; the people of YHWH marched down for him against the mighty.' The 'remnant of the noble' (<em>śārîd lĕʾaddîrîm</em>) marching down to fight suggests that even a partial, remnant-sized force suffices when YHWH fights with them. This is Gideon's lesson (ch7: 300 against 135,000) and the apostolic theology of power in weakness: 'God chose what is weak in the world to shame the strong' (1 Cor 1:27). The size of YHWH's army in any given battle is irrelevant to the outcome; 'the people of YHWH' who march with him always have the decisive advantage.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The tribes listed as having participated — Ephraim, Benjamin, Machir (Manasseh), Zebulun, Issachar — are the northern and central tribes who answered the call. Their participation anticipates the universal call of the gospel: 'Go therefore and make disciples of all nations' (Matt 28:19). The tribal roll call of those who fought alongside Barak is a type of the heavenly roll — the Lamb's book of life (Rev 21:27; 20:15) — which names those who stood with Christ in the battle of the ages.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Issachar's leaders 'came with Deborah, and Issachar was faithful to Barak; into the valley they rushed at his heels.' The willingness to rush into the valley — the plain where Sisera's iron chariots had their greatest advantage — is the courage that trusts the prophetic word over the military odds. Those who followed Barak onto the plain where chariots dominate had to reckon with the battle purely on faith in YHWH's promise. Faith's logic is always this: the word spoken by YHWH is more reliable than the apparent strength of the opposition (Rom 4:20-21: Abraham 'grew strong in his faith... fully convinced that God was able to do what he had promised').</p>",
    "16": "<p>'Why did you sit still among the sheepfolds, to hear the whistling for the flocks?' Reuben's deliberation that kept them back from the battle is rebuked — not for cowardice but for misplaced priority: they stayed with their flocks when the covenant community called. The parable of the great banquet (Luke 14:18-20) enumerates the excuses of those who decline the invitation — land, oxen, wife — and receives the same rebuke: legitimate concerns are allowed to crowd out the supreme summons. Those with 'great searchings of heart' who ultimately do not come are worse off than those who never heard the call.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Dan and Asher are rebuked for remaining at their ships and seashore respectively — the maritime concerns that kept them from land warfare. The rebuke is about priority and solidarity: when the body of YHWH's people is at war, individual tribal interests are subordinate to the common cause. Paul develops this as the theology of the body of Christ: 'If one member suffers, all suffer together; if one member is honored, all rejoice together' (1 Cor 12:26). The tribes that did not come to Deborah's battle fractured the solidarity that covenant warfare requires.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Zebulun is a people who risked their lives to the death; Naphtali, too, on the heights of the field.' The two tribes praised for jeoparding their lives — offered their lives as a stake in the battle — embody the self-giving that characterizes Christ's own offering and calls forth from his followers. 'Greater love has no one than this, that someone lay down his life for his friends' (John 15:13) — Christ said this the same night he went to Gethsemane. Zebulun and Naphtali are the specific tribal territory of Galilee, where Jesus spent most of his earthly ministry (Matt 4:15-16 quoting Isa 9:1-2: 'The land of Zebulun and the land of Naphtali').</p>",
    "19": "<p>'The kings came, they fought; then fought the kings of Canaan, at Taanach, by the waters of Megiddo; they got no spoils of silver.' The Canaanite kings fight but gain nothing — the battle is already decided by YHWH. Megiddo, the site of this battle, becomes in Revelation the locus of the final battle ('Armageddon' from Hebrew <em>har mĕgiddô</em>, Rev 16:16). The Kishon valley victory prefigures the final confrontation between the armies of the Beast and the returning Christ — where, as at Megiddo, the enemy 'gets no spoils' because the outcome is predetermined by the divine warrior's intervention.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'The torrent Kishon swept them away, the ancient torrent, the torrent Kishon.' YHWH's use of the Kishon river to defeat Sisera's chariots — the natural world serving as a weapon of divine judgment — echoes the Red Sea: the water that Israel crossed became the death of Egypt's chariots. Revelation's destruction of Babylon uses river/sea imagery similarly: 'Fallen, fallen is Babylon the great! She has become a dwelling place for demons' (Rev 18:2). The physical waters of creation serve as instruments of the Creator's justice — a pattern that reaches its final expression in the lake of fire (Rev 20:14-15).</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Then loud beat the horses' hooves with the galloping, galloping of his steeds.' The rhythm of Sisera's horses in full flight — running from the battle rather than through it — is the sound of defeated power. The four horsemen of Revelation (Rev 6:1-8) represent the powers of conquest, war, famine, and death that trample the earth; but their final appearance in Rev 19:14 places the white horse under Christ ('The armies of heaven, arrayed in fine linen, white and pure, were following him on white horses'). The hoofbeats at Kishon that signal Canaanite flight become in the NT the hoofbeats of the heavenly cavalry that signals Christ's return.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Curse Meroz, says the angel of YHWH, curse its inhabitants thoroughly, because they did not come to the help of YHWH, to the help of YHWH against the mighty.' The curse of Meroz — for non-participation in YHWH's battle — is the starkest statement in Judges of the covenant obligation to stand with YHWH when he fights. James 4:4 applies the same principle theologically: 'friendship with the world is enmity with God.' Neutrality between Christ and his enemies is impossible: 'Whoever is not with me is against me' (Matt 12:30). The failure to come to the help of YHWH is not passive innocence but active hostility — curse-worthy non-engagement.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'Most blessed of women be Jael, the wife of Heber the Kenite, of tent-dwelling women most blessed.' The blessing of Jael — a Gentile woman, wife of a Kenite — anticipates the blessings declared over Gentile women in the NT lineage of the Messiah: Rahab, Ruth, and the Canaanite woman whose faith Jesus praises (Matt 15:28: 'O woman, great is your faith!'). Jael, like them, acts decisively on behalf of YHWH's purposes from outside the covenant nation. Her double blessing — 'most blessed of women' — is later applied to Mary in Elizabeth's greeting: 'Blessed are you among women, and blessed is the fruit of your womb' (Luke 1:42).</p>",
    "25": "<p>'He asked for water and she gave him milk; she brought him curds in a noble's bowl.' The hospitality-reversal — giving better than was asked for, while serving a destructive purpose — has been read as a type of divine grace that exceeds what we seek: 'Now to him who is able to do far more abundantly than all that we ask or think' (Eph 3:20). Paul uses a similar excess-of-gift logic in Romans 5:20: 'where sin increased, grace abounded all the more.' What Sisera asked for (water) was exceeded (milk); what sin demanded (death) was exceeded by grace (resurrection and eternal life).</p>",
    "26": "<p>'She struck Sisera; she crushed his head; she shattered and pierced his temple.' The 'crushed head' language is the key Christological resonance: Genesis 3:15 promises that the seed of the woman will crush the head of the serpent. Jael — a woman — crushes the head of the enemy. The same verb root (<em>māḥaq</em>) appears in Ps 68:21: 'God will strike the heads of his enemies.' This head-crushing by a woman prefigures the final fulfillment at Calvary, where the seed of the woman (born of a virgin) crushes the head of the ancient serpent (Rev 12:9; 20:2) through the cross and resurrection.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'Between her feet he sank, he fell, he lay still; between her feet he sank, he fell; where he sank, there he fell — dead.' The threefold repetition of 'sank, fell, lay still' is liturgical — the song slows to emphasize the totality of Sisera's defeat. The final phrase 'where he sank, there he fell — dead' is a poetic statement of irreversibility. Paul employs similar repetition in 1 Cor 15:54-55 to emphasize the finality of death's defeat: 'Death is swallowed up in victory. O death, where is your victory? O death, where is your sting?' The song-form of both passages (Deborah's victory song; Paul's doxology) signals that irreversible defeat is best expressed in liturgical form.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'Out of the window she peered, the mother of Sisera wailed through the lattice: Why is his chariot so long in coming? Why tarry the hoofbeats of his chariots?' The mother at the window waiting for a son who will never return is one of Scripture's most haunting images. The waiting that produces not the expected triumph but final silence anticipates the eschatological reversal: those who have built their hope on the military and economic powers of this world will find them ultimately unable to deliver. 'Babylon the great is fallen' (Rev 18:2) — and those who built their fortunes on her will 'stand far off, in fear of her torment, weeping and mourning aloud' (Rev 18:15).</p>",
    "29": "<p>'Her wisest princesses answer; she answers herself as well.' The wise women advising Sisera's mother offer rational comfort based on the logic of conquest — he is delayed because there is so much plunder to distribute. Their wisdom fails because the premise is wrong: Sisera is not distributing plunder but lying dead. The 'wise' counsel that makes sense of the world without accounting for YHWH's action is the wisdom Paul contrasts with the foolishness of the cross: 'Has not God made foolish the wisdom of the world?' (1 Cor 1:20). Sisera's mother's counselors are wise in the way the world thinks; they cannot calculate the Jael variable.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'Are they not finding and dividing the spoil? A womb or two for every man; spoil of dyed materials for Sisera, spoil of dyed materials embroidered, two pieces of dyed work embroidered for the neck as spoil?' The anticipated plunder — including women as war prizes — is the vision that motivates Sisera's mother's false hope. The reduction of human beings to spoil (a 'womb or two') is the epitome of what the powers of this age do: they commodify persons. Christ's redemption runs precisely counter to this: 'you were bought with a price' (1 Cor 6:20) — purchased from exactly this kind of use — 'so glorify God in your body.'</p>",
    "31": "<p>'So may all your enemies perish, O YHWH! But your friends be like the sun as he rises in his might.' The closing benediction of the Song positions the saint's glory — 'like the sun rising in its might' — as the eschatological future of those who love YHWH. Matthew 13:43 quotes this exact image: 'Then the righteous will shine like the sun in the kingdom of their Father.' Daniel 12:3 uses the same image: 'And those who are wise shall shine like the brightness of the sky above.' The Song of Deborah does not end with Sisera's death but with the blazing future of all who align with YHWH — the resurrection glory that the judges' temporary deliverances only anticipate.</p>"
  },
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>Israel 'did evil' again and YHWH gave them into the hand of Midian for seven years. The seven-year oppression has covenant resonance: seven is the sabbatical number, and the land resting under Midianite devastation mirrors the sabbath rest the land 'enjoyed' during Israel's exile (Lev 26:34-35). Gideon's call to deliver Israel from Midian replicates the Exodus pattern on a smaller scale — the oppressor who strips Israel of its produce is overthrown by a deliverer empowered by YHWH's Spirit — and is itself a type of Christ's deliverance of humanity from the oppression of sin that had stripped them of their inheritance.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Israel hid in dens and caves and strongholds 'because of Midian' — the people of God reduced to hiding from their enemies. The same image recurs in Revelation 6:15-16 where the kings of the earth hide in caves from the wrath of the Lamb. Israel hiding from Midian is the humiliation that precedes deliverance; the hiding of the earth's rulers from Christ is the judgment that follows the rejection of deliverance. The people hiding in ch6 need Gideon; those hiding in Rev 6 have refused the one who was offered to them.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The Midianites, Amalekites, and eastern peoples came up whenever Israel had sown — they consumed the crop at the point of greatest vulnerability, immediately after planting. The image of the adversary targeting the sowing rather than the harvest echoes the parable of the sower (Matt 13:19: 'the evil one comes and snatches away what has been sown') — Satan targeting the word at its point of first entry. Gideon's threshing in the winepress (v11) — threshing hidden from view to protect the grain — is the response to this predatory consumption of Israel's labor.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Midianites 'left no sustenance in Israel and no sheep or ox or donkey' — total economic devastation. The stripping of Israel's agricultural surplus mirrors the spiritual poverty Paul describes before the gospel arrives: 'remember that you were at that time separated from Christ, alienated from the commonwealth of Israel and strangers to the covenants of promise, having no hope and without God in the world' (Eph 2:12). The deliverer Gideon is about to restore what seven years of devastation had consumed — as Christ restores what sin had consumed.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Midianites came 'like locusts in number' with their camels — the locust-swarm image is the OT's most visceral picture of consuming devastation (cf. Joel 1-2). Joel's locust army becomes a type of divine judgment in the Apocalypse (Rev 9:3-11: locusts with power like scorpions). That YHWH could raise a deliverer against a locust-scale invasion is the lesson of Joel: 'I will restore to you the years that the swarming locust has eaten' (Joel 2:25) — a promise that anticipates Christ's full restoration of all that sin has consumed.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Israel was brought very low because of Midian. And the people of Israel cried out for help to YHWH.' The low-point cry is the turning point of every judge cycle. Paul describes the same turning point in human salvation: 'while we were still weak, at the right time Christ died for the ungodly' (Rom 5:6) — YHWH responds to the cry of the weak, not the merit of the strong. The Gideon cycle begins with Israel at its most impoverished; it will end with a 300-man army defeating 135,000. The ratio of human weakness to divine power is the consistent testimony of Judges.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'When the people of Israel cried out to YHWH on account of the Midianites, YHWH sent a prophet to the people of Israel.' Before the judge comes the prophet — the word before the deed. The sequence (covenant violation → oppression → cry → prophetic word → raised deliverer) shows that YHWH's first response to Israel's cry is always interpretive: he sends someone to explain why they are suffering before he sends someone to end the suffering. The Word precedes the Act — the pattern of Scripture and incarnation alike: John (the prophet) before Jesus (the deliverer).</p>",
    "8": "<p>The prophet's message recites the covenant prologue ('I am YHWH who brought you up from Egypt') before the covenant indictment ('you did not obey my voice'). The covenant lawsuit form — gift recital, then violation indictment — is the structure of OT prophecy from Moses through the writing prophets. Jesus uses the same form in his messages to the seven churches (Rev 2-3): 'I know your works' + commendation/condemnation + call to repentance. The pattern never changes: the response to suffering is first diagnosis of cause, then promised remedy.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'I delivered you from the hand of the Egyptians and from the hand of all who oppressed you, and drove them out before you and gave you their land.' The covenant prologue spoken through the anonymous prophet establishes what YHWH has already done as the basis for what he is about to do. Romans 8:32 applies the same logic to the cross: 'He who did not spare his own Son but gave him up for us all, how will he not also with him graciously give us all things?' The first gift (the Exodus, the land) is the guarantee of further gifts; the first sacrifice (Christ) is the guarantee of all covenant blessings.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'I said to you, I am YHWH your God; you shall not fear the gods of the Amorites in whose land you dwell. But you have not obeyed my voice.' The prohibition is not merely religious but relational — 'I am YHWH your God' makes idolatry an act of personal betrayal. John 14:15 makes the relational-obedience connection explicit: 'If you love me, you will keep my commandments.' The prophetic indictment of v10 — covenant privilege squandered through disobedience — is the background against which God's grace in sending Gideon (and, ultimately, Christ) is most clearly seen: he acts despite non-compliance, not because of it.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Gideon asks for a sign to confirm that it is truly YHWH speaking: 'Please show me a sign that it is you who speak with me.' The request for a sign is not rebuked — YHWH grants it in vv19-21. But the greater confirmation throughout Judges and the NT is the fulfillment of the word itself: 'Blessed are those who have not seen and yet have believed' (John 20:29). Isaiah's criterion for true prophecy — 'if the thing does not come to pass, it is not spoken by YHWH' (Deut 18:22) — is fulfilled completely in Jesus, whose every prediction came to pass. The sign Gideon requests is granted; the sign of the resurrection exceeds all others.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Please do not depart from here until I come to you and bring out my present and set it before you.' Gideon's request — 'Do not depart' — is the prayer of one who recognizes that the divine presence is the essential thing, not its benefits. The same prayer echoes in Moses: 'If your presence will not go with me, do not bring us up from here' (Exod 33:15). The disciples on the Emmaus road make the same request unknowingly: 'Stay with us, for it is toward evening' (Luke 24:29). The repeated prayer to the divine Presence not to depart is answered finally in Christ's promise: 'I am with you always, to the end of the age' (Matt 28:20).</p>",
    "19": "<p>Gideon prepares a young goat and unleavened cakes — a substantial meal from his own household's meager resources — to bring to his guest. The sacrificial character of this offering (a kid, unleavened bread, broth) anticipates the meal's transformation into an offering in vv20-21. The Last Supper similarly transforms a meal (bread and wine) into a sacrificial memorial: 'This is my body given for you; do this in remembrance of me' (Luke 22:19). The pattern runs through Scripture: the meal that becomes an offering, the offering that becomes the basis of covenant relationship.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Take the meat and the unleavened cakes, and put them on this rock, and pour the broth over them.' The Angel's instruction redirects the food from consumption to sacrifice — the same elements that would have been a shared meal become a burnt offering. This transformation from guest-meal to altar-offering is the logic of sacrifice: what is given as hospitality to God becomes what God receives as worship. Paul applies this to Christian self-offering: 'I appeal to you therefore, brothers, by the mercies of God, to present your bodies as a living sacrifice, holy and acceptable to God, which is your spiritual worship' (Rom 12:1).</p>",
    "21": "<p>(Continued from present entry at v22) — the fire from the rock that consumed Gideon's offering is the same fire that consumed Elijah's offering on Carmel (1 Kings 18:38) and that the Spirit manifests at Pentecost (Acts 2:3: 'tongues as of fire'). Divine fire consuming an offering is the signature of YHWH's acceptance — the altar fire that never went out in the Tabernacle (Lev 6:13) is the perpetual sign of accepted worship. Christ's self-offering was consumed by divine judgment ('it was the will of YHWH to crush him,' Isa 53:10) and accepted — his resurrection is the smoke ascending from the fire of the cross.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'But YHWH said to him, Peace be to you. Do not fear; you shall not die.' The divine 'peace' declared after theophanic terror is the resolution of the problem that fallen humanity faces in divine encounter. Gideon had said 'I have seen the Angel of YHWH face to face' — and expected death (cf. Gen 32:30; Exod 33:20). The 'Peace' granted him preempts death. Christ's resurrection appearance to the disciples begins identically: 'Peace be with you' (John 20:19, 21, 26) — spoken by the risen Jesus whose presence they had feared. The shalom of the Angel to Gideon is a type of the shalom of Christ to his disciples across the locked door.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'Take your father's bull and the second bull seven years old, and pull down the altar of Baal that your father has, and cut down the Asherah that is beside it.' The first act of Gideon's calling is not military but reformatory — destroy the false worship at the center of his own household before he goes out to fight Midian. Christ's temple cleansing (John 2:13-17; Matt 21:12-13) follows the same logic: before the proclamation of the kingdom, the house of worship must be purified. 'Judgment begins with the household of God' (1 Pet 4:17). The reform of Gideon's father's household is the microcosm of the purification Christ brings to his Father's house.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'Then build an altar to YHWH your God on the top of the stronghold here, with stones laid in due order.' The replacing of Baal's altar with YHWH's altar — on the same site — is the covenantal displacement that the gospel enacts: not merely removing the false but installing the true in its place. The 'stones in due order' (<em>bamma'arākāh</em>) on the newly built altar anticipate the 'living stones' of 1 Peter 2:5: 'you yourselves like living stones are being built up as a spiritual house, to be a holy priesthood, to offer spiritual sacrifices acceptable to God through Jesus Christ.' The altar Gideon builds is a type of the temple Christ builds — his church.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Gideon did as YHWH commanded but did it at night, 'because he was too afraid of his family and the men of the town to do it by day.' The fear acknowledged in Gideon's night operation is not condemned by the narrator — he did the deed, which is what mattered. Peter's three denials, committed out of fear, do not disqualify him from Christ's restoration and commission (John 21:15-19). The NT does not celebrate fear but recognizes that obedience under fear is still obedience: 'The Spirit you received does not make you slaves, so that you live in fear again; rather, the Spirit you received brought about your adoption' (Rom 8:15). The Spirit who later clothes Gideon (v34) replaces his nighttime fear.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The men of the city discover the torn-down altar of Baal in the morning — the night work is revealed by daylight. Paul applies this dawn-revelation pattern to the Christian life: 'The night is far gone; the day is at hand. So then let us cast off the works of darkness and put on the armor of light' (Rom 13:12). The works done in darkness are exposed by the day; what Gideon did in secret becomes the public challenge of v29-31. Christ's own work of defeating death happened 'in the night' — but the resurrection morning made it public to the world (1 Cor 15:20: 'Christ has been raised from the dead, the firstfruits of those who have fallen asleep').</p>",
    "29": "<p>'And they said to one another, Who has done this thing? And after they had searched and inquired, they said, Gideon the son of Joash has done this thing.' The investigation and identification of Gideon as the reformer is a type of the recognition scenes in John's Gospel: when confronted with the work of God, people ask 'who did this?' — and the answer reveals the one who has acted on YHWH's behalf. 'The works that I do in my Father's name bear witness about me' (John 10:25). Works that disrupt the existing order of false worship always provoke the question of authorship — and the answer reveals the divine agent.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'The men of the town said to Joash, Bring out your son, that he may die, for he has broken down the altar of Baal and cut down the Asherah beside it.' The townspeople demand Gideon's death for destroying Baal's altar — the same demand that the religious establishment makes of Jesus for disrupting the Temple. John 11:50 gives the logic: 'it is better for you that one man should die for the people.' The pattern is identical: reform → perceived threat to the established order → death demand. Joash's defense of Gideon (v31) anticipates the defenders of Christ who recognized that YHWH, not Baal, was the true God.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Joash's defense: 'Will you contend for Baal? Or will you save him? Whoever contends for him shall be put to death by morning. If he is a god, let him contend for himself, because his altar has been broken down.' The logic is identical to Elijah's on Carmel (1 Kings 18:27: 'Call louder, perhaps he is asleep') — a god who cannot defend his own altar is no god. Christ's resurrection is the ultimate vindication that the Father 'contends' for his Son: 'he was declared to be the Son of God in power according to the Spirit of holiness by his resurrection from the dead' (Rom 1:4). The true God vindicates himself; false gods cannot.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Gideon is renamed Jerubbaal ('Let Baal contend against him') on the day that the townspeople make their demand. The renaming anticipates the irony: Baal cannot contend, so the name Jerubbaal is forever a monument to Baal's impotence and YHWH's vindication of his servant. The naming pattern — giving a new name that embeds the story of divine action — runs through Scripture: Abram/Abraham, Jacob/Israel, Simon/Peter. Christ gives a new name to the overcomer in Rev 2:17: 'I will give him a white stone, with a new name written on the stone that no one knows except the one who receives it' — a name that encodes the personal story of divine victory.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'Then all the Midianites and the Amalekites and the people of the East came together, and they crossed the Jordan and encamped in the Valley of Jezreel.' The gathering of the coalition against YHWH's newly-commissioned deliverer is the pattern of all opposition to divine redemption: as soon as the deliverer is raised up, the enemy mobilizes. Revelation 20:7-9 describes the final gathering of the nations against 'the camp of the saints and the beloved city' — an opposition that cannot succeed because 'fire came down from heaven and consumed them.' The Valley of Jezreel/Megiddo is the shadow of Armageddon.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Gideon sends messengers through Asher, Zebulun, and Naphtali — the same northern Galilean tribes praised in the Song of Deborah (5:18) for risking their lives, and the territory of Jesus's earthly ministry (Matt 4:12-17). The messengers who summon the tribes to battle are types of the apostolic messengers of the gospel: 'How beautiful are the feet of those who preach the good news' (Rom 10:15, citing Isa 52:7). Every calling of the people of God to assemble for battle is a type of the apostolic call that gathers the church.</p>",
    "37": "<p>'Behold, I am laying a fleece of wool on the threshing floor. If there is dew on the fleece only, and it is dry on all the ground, then I shall know that you will save Israel by my hand, as you have spoken.' Gideon's two fleece tests — fleece wet/ground dry, then fleece dry/ground wet — are requests for supernatural confirmation of an already-spoken promise. YHWH grants them patiently, though the promise had been clearly spoken. The NT equivalent is Thomas: 'Unless I see in his hands the mark of the nails... I will never believe' (John 20:25) — and Christ appears to Thomas with exactly the evidence he requested. Divine patience with weak faith is itself a type of grace.</p>",
    "38": "<p>'And it was so. When he rose early next morning and squeezed the fleece, he wrung enough dew from the fleece to fill a bowl with water.' The miraculous surplus — enough dew to fill a bowl, drawn from wool when the surrounding ground was dry — is the sign of divine specificity. YHWH's answers to prayer are not approximate but exact: 'Before they call I will answer; while they are yet speaking I will hear' (Isa 65:24). The precise fulfillment of the fleece-sign strengthens rather than replaces faith; it prepares Gideon for the greater test of Judges 7 where 300 must face 135,000 without any material advantage at all.</p>",
    "39": "<p>'Then Gideon said to God, Let not your anger burn against me; let me speak just once more. Please let me test just once more with the fleece.' Gideon's apology for asking again — 'Let not your anger burn against me' — reflects the posture of covenant petition before a holy God. Yet YHWH does not rebuke him; he simply grants the second sign. Abraham bargained with YHWH over Sodom down to ten righteous people (Gen 18:32) without being rebuked; Jacob wrestled until dawn and was blessed (Gen 32:26-29). Christ's parable of the persistent widow (Luke 18:1-8) explicitly encourages this kind of repeated, confident petition: 'Will not God give justice to his elect, who cry to him day and night?'</p>"
  }
}

